<h2>Campaigning Online: The Internet as Reinforcer, Motivator and Fund-Raiser</h2>
<h4>CCTP 796: Electoral Campaign Communications / April 26, 2004</h4>

<p>As the story goes, former Vermont governor Howard Dean revolutionized the use of the Internet for political campaigning in 2003 and early 2004, employing the medium for everything from converting and mobilizing supporters to (perhaps most importantly) raising unparalleled sums of money. That Dean eventually self-destructed in the primaries &mdash; attributable as much to outside factors as to Dean's campaign itself &mdash; does not underestimate the significance of his contribution to the proverbial political strategic playbook.</p>
<p>In the 2004 presidential campaign season, major-party presidential candidates have employed the Internet to an unprecedented degree to communicate their campaign messages. However, despite the Internet's potential as a means to reach out to undecided or easily swayed voters, the most effective functions of candidate Web sites continue to be 1) soliciting and processing donations online; 2) strengthening and reinforcing existing voter support; 3) mobilizing volunteer efforts; and 4) disseminating campaign messages to the mass media. This paper will focus specifically on the online efforts of the Kerry and Dean presidential campaigns, with occasional mentions of third-party groups, such as the Democratic National Committee and MoveOn.org.</p>

<h3>The Internet Audience</h3>
<p>The Internet often is hailed for its revolutionary potential to further democratize politics, offering unmediated communication between a candidate and his or her potential supporters, adding greater transparency to the political process (for example, the ability to study candidates' Federal Election Commission financial filings; see opensecrets.org) and allowing for a new kind of grassroots political organization and mobilization. Michael Cornfield and Johan Seiger write, &quot;The Internet is best understood, in comparison with other media, as a locus that uniquely combines unlimited consideration and direct response.&quot; [<a href="#1">1</a>] Site visitors have an unlimited amount of time to peruse, absorb, and evaluate political information presented online (as compared to the limited exposure of watching a brief television advertisement) and are able to submit feedback &mdash; in the form of e-mail, campaign contributions, or the like &mdash; directly and immediately to the campaign (without the delay of waiting for mail delivery or for a check to clear).</p>
<p>Particularly important for third-party and &quot;upstart&quot; candidates, but also important to mainstream candidates, is the ability the Internet medium affords for candidates to communicate directly with their audience at minimal cost and with minimal worry about how (or if) their messages might be conveyed through the mass media. &quot;[I]t is not always safe to trust intermediaries to be fare and accurate, and it can be illuminating when candidates present their issues in their own way, with their own choices of emphasis and rhetoric,&quot;  writes Peter Levine. [<a href="#2">2</a>] In a single, easily accessible venue, campaigns can communicate directly with undecided voters, existing supporters, the media, and any other interested groups or individuals who choose to visit the site. And instead of strict one-way communication between leader and audience, visitors to campaign Web sites are, ideally, able to correspond with the candidate and/or his or her campaign organization &mdash; or with each other. At the same time, online communications are often cheaper than direct mail or paid media advertising, and offer the potential for much more immediate response.</p>
<p>According to a February 2004 Nielsen//NetRatings study, [<a href="#3">3</a>] nearly 70 percent of Americans, or 204.3 million people, have some kind of access to the Internet. Demographically, Internet users are more affluent than the general population (and the fastest-growing segment of the Internet population is households with income of $75,000 and up). [<a href="#4">4</a>] These affluent users are more likely to be subscribers to high-speed broadband Internet service, which is more costly than the slower dial-up service. An April 2004 Pew Internet and American Life study found that broadband users are more likely to spend longer periods of time online and to perform a greater variety of online tasks. [<a href="#5">5</a>]</p>
<p>Internet users are more politically active as well: A March 2004 Nielsen//NetRatings study [<a href="#6">6</a>] found that 86 percent of online users are registered voters, and 77 percent voted in the 2000 presidential election, compared to the offline population, where 70 percent are registered and 60 percent voted in 2000. Online users also reported greater participation in offline political activities: 50 percent had signed a political petition, 37 percent had written to an elected official, and 28 percent had donated to a political campaign or organization. And about 25 percent of people age 30 and younger report conducting at least one form of political activity &mdash; be it candidate/issue research, discussion/chat, or the like &mdash; <em>online</em>. [<a href="#7">7</a>] </p>
<p>All of these demographic qualities suggest that the online population, being more likely to show interest and participate in political affairs, is an ideal audience to target for political campaign messages.</p>

<h3>Outreach</h3>
<p>One of the main functions of a candidate Web site is to keep its visitors informed about the latest developments regarding the candidate. A population accustomed to constantly changing online news sites expects that a leading candidate Web site be similarly up-to-date and frequently changing as the campaign goes on. The main feature on the Kerry campaign home page changes on a daily basis, usually related to a campaign event, an issue in the media, or an attack on/response to his opponent. It also has become common for the campaign to prominently release any public disclosures via the Web site, such as Kerry's April 23, 2004, release of medical records from Kerry's time in the Navy. [<a href="#8">8</a>] This is a smart tactic to boost both the visibility and the relevancy of the campaign Web site, and maybe attract a few site visitors who might not otherwise have come to the site, exposing them not only to the information they came for, but to Kerry's overall campaign message as well. For example, it cannot be a coincidence that the first document on the page listing Kerry's medical records [<a href="#9">9</a>] is about the candidate's war medals.</p>
<p>In keeping with today's accelerated news cycle, the campaigns also have taken to attacking and counter-attacking each other via the campaign Web sites. The Kerry site, for instance, has a feature called the &quot;D-Bunker,&quot; [<a href="#10">10</a>] a weblog-style compendium of the Kerry campaign's latest responses to Bush &quot;false statements&quot; and debunkings of &quot;right-wing myths.&quot; (In response, GeorgeWBush.com has a &quot;Kerry Media Center&quot; section with a special &quot;D-Bunker Buster&quot; feature.) Washington Post media critic Howard Kurtz followed the rapid-fire volley/parry of the dueling campaigns in one of his columns:</p>

<blockquote>
<p>Technology and the sheer acceleration of news coverage have combined to produce a presidential campaign that is faster and more frenetic than ever before, reducing response time to mere minutes. Although campaigns have been in rapid response mode since the days of Bill Clinton's 1992 war room, Bush and Kerry operatives now flood reporters with e-mail attacks and BlackBerry responses, arrange conference calls and wage a Web war complete with online video &mdash; a far cry from the faxed statements of an earlier era.</p>
<p>The stakes are considerable. In a campaign that is striking for its early intensity and daily negativity, each side is trying to frame the debate &mdash; Bush by painting Kerry as big on taxes and soft on defense, and Kerry by depicting the president as a failure on the economy and Iraq. Each newspaper headline, television sound bite or Internet posting burnishes or blemishes the candidates' image. [<a href="#11">11</a>]</p>
</blockquote>

<p>It is important to recognize the significance of the interaction between online and traditional media in conveying a campaign message. In this case, these online &quot;debunker&quot; features offer political writers plenty of easy material to cover the back-and-forth volleys of negative campaigning between the two candidates. Mainstream media's covering these online skirmishes provides more exposure for the candidates and for their Web sites (although it is debatable just how <em>useful</em> that exposure, often covered as &quot;campaign color&quot; rather than substance, is in helping the voting public make informed political judgments).</p>
<p>It is important to recognize the Internet as a <em>tool</em> for reaching a broad audience, but should not be employed to the exclusion of traditional media. As Cornfield and Seiger write, &quot;The Internet is not a replacement for television, but it can be, in the hands of an innovative candidate, a substantial, and perhaps decisive, supplement.&quot; [<a href="#12">12</a>] The major political campaigns do not focus their online efforts on voter &quot;conversion&quot; &mdash; winning over undecided voters &mdash; because appealing to potential voters through other media has proven far more effective. Mainstream campaign sites by no means try to exclude potential voters; rather, while these sites do provide candidate and issue information for undecided voters, all-out efforts to attract and convert undecided voters is not the core focus of their online operations.</p>

